I enjoyed Shelby.

I have been now for three years.

Describe those two.

Charlie Thomas is somebody that if you knew he was in a burning building, you'd dash in to get him because you wouldn't be sure he'd go out on his own.
Charlie doesn't really get very excited about anything.
But he was a good track coach.

We've got some.

Dave Hartman, who we brought in two years ago as a long-distance coach, is doing real, real well at attracting athletes.
And so we're going to see some changes.
Of all the coaches and all the sports that you have known here, to which one would you give the highest mark given what they had to work with?
Who did the best job with what they had to work with, whether they won championships or not?

I don't know.

Mark has done a good job.

I think a couple of years, RC has done a real good job.
And a couple of years, Shelby did a real good job.
And again, I'm not going to ask the negative.
Which one do you think of all the coaches here had the most spotless record in terms of their adhering to the rules?
Who followed the rules most closely?

Do you have any ideal role model announcers from either the past or the present?
The only man that I ever listened to that I really tried to follow was an old man who did the Chicago Cubs for years and years and years named Pat Piper.
And he sat on a chair down behind home plate.
He didn't even sit in the press box.
And all he did was introduce the batter and then change the pitchers, and that's it.
And that's pretty much what I've tried to do.
And Dave South changed me, oh gosh, I suppose it's five years ago now.
When they built that new scoreboard, they paid good money.
So advertisers paid good money for that.
And Dave said, we want them to have to look at the scoreboard.
So he said, just tell who carried the ball, who made the tackle, and that's it.
Don't tell the yardage or anything unless they make over 10 yards and go.
And don't need to tell them it's first down.
They can look at the scoreboard and tell it's first down.
So I cut back a lot of what I've done, and I like it.
You know, you get tired of listening to people after a while.
And so many times they're late.
And so if you just tell who's carrying the ball, who made the tackle, then get off and wait for the next play.
Substitutions, you can't keep up with them.
There's no point in trying.
Back in the days when you had limited substitution or unlimited, or really no substitute at all, if there was a substitute, you could get him in the game.
I remember seeing the last game that Niall Kinnick played at the University of Iowa in 1939.
Iowa used 13 players that day.

Describe how your task, your assignment,
change if it did in all the years you were a faculty member?
Once I got into diagnostic pathology, I found a home.
I'm a great why man.
You never do know why, but you always wish you did.

And it was really a, really a, and plus it has such a broader spectrum.
When you treat same thing every day.

I got into diagnostic.

or not fit to eat based on what you see and that I got a real tremendous exposure to disease, the changes disease can produce in animals
and then having to decide whether that change could be removed just by excoriation or whether it was affecting the entire carcass.
And I really found it to be exciting.
And this was for all sorts of animals?
Well, in meat inspection, I started out in poultry with turkeys and chickens, and then I switched to cattle and sheep.
and hogs.
And then when I got here in veterinary school and also in Auburn as well, then you're doing the whole thing, a whole range of small animals, various breeds of small animals, cattle.
We didn't have a lot of exotic animals come through postmortem when I was there, but we'd have some.
Now this was a formal course for fourth year students?
Pretty much so, yes.
Here, yes.
normally how many students would be in each class?
Well, when you get down to the clinical years now, in post-mortem, of course, I hadn't worked in post-mortem since 75.
I went to clinical pathology in 75.
But we would have between six and eight in a group.
Would they rotate?
Did you have all the members in the class in the semester?
Yes.
And describe what your week routine in those classes would be.
Were you there all day, every day?
This would be about 72 or 73.
Bridges switched me over to teaching the pathology course to the seniors in biomedical science.
And this was a laboratory course that had, when we first started, it had six hours of lab, one hour of lecture, and then we added another hour of lecture.
So it was six hours of lab, two hours of lecture a week.
And I had two sections.
So this filled up my time pretty well.
But I would still spend one day a week in the diagnostics lab over in the small animal clinic, above the small animal clinic.
working over there.
But I had 12 hours of laboratory a week in class, plus two hours of lecture, and this really kept me busy.
describe those biomedical science students?

And when he first started it, he started it to produce
A whole bunch of junior started veterinary assistant programs and the Texas in Waco started one.

And what has evolved though now here on the campus is that it is essentially the pre-medical study curriculum for all areas of medicine.
Dentistry, medicine, human medicine, podiatry,
They've got now nearly 2,000 majors in the biomedical science program.
It is just awesome.

anybody for that matter is that you take all the information that they give you as far as their prerequisites and everything is concerned and then you start picking them on the number from the top down I want this one I want this one I want this one and when you get your quota filled

You have just selected people in which you believe they will do what you want them to do in the way you want it done.
